## DatabricksAuth — disable CloudFetch in Apps mode

Context: Production deploy of the dev sandbox app crashed during
``DigitalTwin.run_build_task`` whenever the triplestore VIEW grew
past the inline-results threshold:

```
Failed to read from VIEW benoit_cayla.ontobricks_020.triplestore_bigcustomers_V1:
HTTP request failed: HTTPSConnectionPool(host='us-west-2.storage.cloud.databricks.com',
port=443): … [Errno 111] Connection refused
```

Root cause: the `databricks-sql-connector` defaults to **CloudFetch**.
Past a row/byte threshold the warehouse stops streaming results back
through the Thrift channel and instead returns a presigned URL on
``*.storage.cloud.databricks.com``; the client then opens a fresh
HTTPS connection to that internal storage host to download chunks.
The Databricks Apps network sandbox can't reach that host on 443
(``Connection refused``), so the very first chunk download dies and
the whole query fails. Local PAT runs always worked because a laptop
has open egress.

Small VIEWs / single-row probes never hit this code path (their
results stay inline), which is why ``test_connection`` was green and
why the bug only surfaced on real workloads like the bigcustomers
build.

Fix: when running inside a Databricks App, pass
``use_cloud_fetch=False`` to ``databricks.sql.connect(...)``. The
connector then keeps the inline Thrift result protocol on every
query, going through the workspace endpoint we are already
authenticated against. Local-dev PAT mode keeps CloudFetch enabled
for performance — the flag is only set when ``is_app_mode`` is true.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/databricks/DatabricksAuth.py
   - `get_sql_connection_params()`: when `self.is_app_mode`, set
     `params["use_cloud_fetch"] = False` before adding the access
     token. PAT path is unchanged. Updated the docstring with the
     network-sandbox rationale so the next person reading the file
     understands why local dev and Apps differ.

Modified files:
- src/back/core/databricks/DatabricksAuth.py

Tests: `uv run pytest -q` → 2028 passed in 66.27s (no behaviour
change in PAT/local-dev mode; the new `use_cloud_fetch=False` only
applies when `DATABRICKS_APP_PORT` is set, which is not the case in
CI). Smoke: `python -c "from back.core.databricks.DatabricksAuth
import DatabricksAuth; …"` → params dict carries
`use_cloud_fetch=False` only when `DATABRICKS_APP_PORT` is set.

## Cohort designer — enforce camelCase rule names

Context: Cohort rule names previously accepted free-form text
("Exempt staffing pool"). The label was slugged to `exempt_staffing_pool`
for the registry id, which forked the human-facing name from the
identifier and made downstream consumers (URL params, UC table
suffixes, registry keys, Stage 2 agent prompts) carry two slightly
different strings for the same rule. The form now constrains the
rule name to camelCase (alphanumeric only, starting with a letter),
which is also a valid identifier — so `id = label` and there is one
canonical name across the stack.

Changes:

1. src/front/static/query/js/query-cohorts.js
   - New `_toCamelCase(s)` helper: splits on any non-alphanumeric run,
     capitalises each segment's first character, drops a leading-digit
     prefix. Used for paste handling and for normalising labels from
     the Stage 2 NL agent.
   - New `_isValidRuleName(s)` helper enforcing
     `^[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9]*$`.
   - `_hookLabelInput()`: `input` event strips invalid characters live
     (with cursor preservation) instead of slugging into a parallel id.
     New `paste` handler camelizes the pasted text in-place so a user
     can paste "Exempt staffing pool" and land on "ExemptStaffingPool".
     The displayed `cohortRuleId` echoes `rule.label` directly for new
     rules — no more slug fork.
